Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The data I chose is TMDb movie data which are cleaned from original data on Kaggle website. This data contains some information about nearly ten thousand movies collected from The Movie Database. below there is a table shows the columns names in datasest and their significance:

Columne Name Signicance
id A unique identifier for each movie.
imdb_id the movie identifier as in the IMDB dataset.
popularity A numeric quantity specifying the movie popularity.
budget The budget in which the movie was made.
revenue The worldwide revenue generated by the movie.
original_title The title of the movie before translation or adaptation.
cast The name of lead and supporting actors.
homepage A link to the homepage of the movie.
director The name of the film director
tagline A line describe the message of the film.
keywords The keywords or tags related to the movie.
overview A brief description of the movie.
runtime The running time of the movie in minutes.
genres The genre of the movie,drama, Action, Comedy , etc.
production_companies The production house of the movie.
release_date The date on which it was released.
vote_count the count of votes recieved.
vote_average average ratings the movie recieved.
release_year The year on which film was released.
budget_adj show the budget of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.
revenue_adj show revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

The main questions i will build my anlalysis around it:¶

  • What are relations between popularity, budget and rating?
  • What are the most succesful movies(in earnings)?
  • Who is the Director produced the best movies in 2010?

First I will import some useful packages which are:

  • Numpy: a library for Python adding support for large, multi-dimensional arrays and matrices, along with a large collection of high-level mathematical functions to operate on these arrays.

  • Matplotlib: Matplotlib is a plotting library for Python and its numerical mathematics extension NumPy.
  • Seaborn: a Python data visualization library based on matplotlib and provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive and informative statistical graphics.

The limitations of first wrangling process¶

  • I found there are alot of missing values need to handle in: imdb_id,homepage, cast, director, tagline, keywords, overview, genres, and production_companies.
  • There are many columns we don't need in our anlyasis like :(imdb_id,tagline,homepage,keywords, budget_adj,revenue_adj)
  • Fortunately, we have just one duplicated value
  • release date column incorrect format.
  • there are movies with zero budget value and zero revenue value, means there values have not been recorded.
  • movies with zero runtime value.

Data Cleaning¶

  1. correct data types
  2. droping unwanted columns
  3. handling missing data rows
  4. delete duplicated rows
  5. handling zeroes values in budget and runtime columns

Research Question 2: What are the most succesful movies(in earnings)?¶

To answer this question i need to know the pure gains of every movie then sort all of them to know which movie got the most earnings. First i will make a profit columne from the two columns revenue and budget then sort movies according to profit columne then the top movies will be the most successful.

In [39]:
# First i will make a profit columne from the two columns revenue and budget
tmdb_df['profit'] = tmdb_df['revenue']-tmdb_df['budget']

In [43]:
#function to find top 10 for a chosen column which sorted the given column and select the top ten
# then plot the result
def top_ten(col_name,size=10):
    sorted_df = pd.DataFrame(tmdb_df[col_name].sort_values(ascending=False))[:size]
    sorted_df['original_title'] = tmdb_df['original_title']
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    sns.barplot(x=col_name, y='original_title', data=sorted_df, label=col_name)
    plt.xlabel(col_name)
    plt.ylabel('')
    plt.title('Top 10 Movies in: ' + col_name)
    plt.legend()
In [44]:
top_ten('profit')

Conclusions¶

From previous analysis we found some useful information :

In first researsh question we could notice that:¶

From histograms and box plots we can notice that most of movies has an average rating between 5.5 and 7. Also we noticed that most of movies has received a number of votes between 10 and 1000. From relations plots we noticed that the revenue increases with increasing in Popularity and also between popularity and vote count.

Limitations:¶

  • I found there are alot of missing values need to handle in: imdb_id,homepage, cast, director, tagline, keywords, overview, genres, and production_companies.
  • There are many columns we don't need in our anlyasis like :(imdb_id,tagline,homepage,keywords, budget_adj,revenue_adj)
  • Fortunately, we have just one duplicated value
  • release date column incorrect format.
  • there are movies with zero budget value and zero revenue value, means there values have not been recorded.
  • movies with zero runtime value.
